	<h2>Understanding Stockton's Climate Challenges</h2>

	<h3>Temperature Extremes</h3>
	<p>The Central Valley experiences some of California's most extreme temperature variations:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Summer highs:</strong> 95-105°F regularly from June through September</li>
		<li><strong>Winter lows:</strong> 35-45°F common from December through February</li>
		<li><strong>Daily fluctuations:</strong> 40+ degree temperature swings damage many materials</li>
		<li><strong>Extended heat periods:</strong> Weeks of consecutive 100°F+ days stress fence materials</li>
		<li><strong>Freeze events:</strong> Occasional freezing temperatures cause expansion/contraction</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Moisture and Humidity Patterns</h3>
	<p>Our moisture patterns create unique challenges:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Wet winters:</strong> 15-20 inches of concentrated rainfall November through March</li>
		<li><strong>Dry summers:</strong> Near-zero precipitation for 5-6 months annually</li>
		<li><strong>Tule fog:</strong> Dense fog keeps fences damp for extended periods</li>
		<li><strong>High humidity events:</strong> Occasional humid periods accelerate wood rot</li>
		<li><strong>Rapid dry-wet cycles:</strong> Materials expand and contract repeatedly</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Sun Exposure and UV Damage</h3>
	<p>Intense California sun affects fence longevity:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>300+ sunny days:</strong> Constant UV exposure degrades materials</li>
		<li><strong>Intense summer sun:</strong> Surface temperatures can exceed 150°F</li>
		<li><strong>Directional damage:</strong> South and west-facing fences age faster</li>
		<li><strong>Color fading:</strong> UV radiation bleaches and discolors surfaces</li>
		<li><strong>Material breakdown:</strong> Plastics become brittle, wood grays and cracks</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Wood Fencing in Stockton's Climate</h2>

	<h3>How Wood Performs in Central Valley Conditions</h3>
	<p>Wood remains the most popular fence material in Stockton, but climate significantly impacts its performance:</p>

	<p><strong>Advantages in Our Climate:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Natural insulation:</strong> Handles temperature extremes better than metal</li>
		<li><strong>Proven track record:</strong> Decades of successful use in the region</li>
		<li><strong>Repairable:</strong> Individual boards easily replaced after storm damage</li>
		<li><strong>Aesthetic warmth:</strong> Natural appearance complements Stockton architecture</li>
		<li><strong>Cost-effective initially:</strong> Lower upfront investment than alternatives</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Challenges in Our Climate:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Moisture damage:</strong> Winter rains cause warping, splitting, and rot</li>
		<li><strong>Sun damage:</strong> UV exposure grays wood and degrades surface integrity</li>
		<li><strong>Expansion/contraction:</strong> Temperature swings cause boards to crack</li>
		<li><strong>Maintenance intensive:</strong> Requires sealing/staining every 2-3 years</li>
		<li><strong>Shorter lifespan:</strong> 10-15 years typical in our climate vs 20+ elsewhere</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Best Wood Types for Stockton</h3>

	<p><strong>Cedar:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Climate performance:</strong> Natural oils resist moisture and insects excellently</li>
		<li><strong>Durability:</strong> 15-20 years with proper maintenance in Central Valley</li>
		<li><strong>Maintenance:</strong> Requires sealing every 2-3 years to maintain color</li>
		<li><strong>Cost:</strong> $30-45 per linear foot installed</li>
		<li><strong>Best application:</strong> Privacy fences where aesthetics matter</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Pressure-Treated Pine:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Climate performance:</strong> Chemical treatment resists rot and insects well</li>
		<li><strong>Durability:</strong> 10-15 years in Stockton conditions with maintenance</li>
		<li><strong>Maintenance:</strong> Annual inspection, sealing every 2-3 years</li>
		<li><strong>Cost:</strong> $25-35 per linear foot installed</li>
		<li><strong>Best application:</strong> Budget-conscious privacy applications</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Redwood:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Climate performance:</strong> Superior moisture resistance, ages beautifully</li>
		<li><strong>Durability:</strong> 20-25 years possible with proper care in our climate</li>
		<li><strong>Maintenance:</strong> Minimal if allowed to gray naturally, sealing optional</li>
		<li><strong>Cost:</strong> $35-50 per linear foot installed</li>
		<li><strong>Best application:</strong> Premium installations, heritage properties</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Maintenance Requirements for Wood in Stockton</h3>
	<p>Wood fences require consistent maintenance to survive our climate:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Annual inspection:</strong> Check for rot, loose boards, and damage (October)</li>
		<li><strong>Cleaning:</strong> Power wash gently in spring to remove mildew and debris</li>
		<li><strong>Sealing/staining:</strong> Reapply every 2-3 years before winter (September-October)</li>
		<li><strong>Drainage maintenance:</strong> Keep soil graded away from posts year-round</li>
		<li><strong>Vegetation control:</strong> Maintain 6-12 inch clearance from plants</li>
		<li><strong>Board replacement:</strong> Replace damaged boards promptly to prevent spread</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Vinyl Fencing in Stockton's Climate</h2>

	<h3>How Vinyl Performs in Central Valley Conditions</h3>
	<p>Vinyl fencing has grown increasingly popular in Stockton due to low maintenance requirements:</p>

	<p><strong>Advantages in Our Climate:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Moisture immunity:</strong> Won't rot, warp, or absorb water regardless of rain</li>
		<li><strong>Low maintenance:</strong> No painting, sealing, or staining ever required</li>
		<li><strong>Insect proof:</strong> Termites and carpenter ants can't damage vinyl</li>
		<li><strong>Long lifespan:</strong> 20-30 years typical in Central Valley conditions</li>
		<li><strong>Color retention:</strong> Quality vinyl maintains appearance for decades</li>
		<li><strong>Easy cleaning:</strong> Hose off dirt and debris, no special care needed</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Challenges in Our Climate:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Heat expansion:</strong> Expands significantly in 100°F+ temperatures</li>
		<li><strong>Brittleness:</strong> Can become brittle in rare freezing conditions</li>
		<li><strong>Wind vulnerability:</strong> Some styles catch wind more than wood</li>
		<li><strong>Impact damage:</strong> Can crack if struck, unlike wood which dents</li>
		<li><strong>Color limitations:</strong> Fewer color options than painted wood</li>
		<li><strong>Higher upfront cost:</strong> More expensive initially than wood options</li>
	</ul>

